04470nam a22006735i 9780813554310DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2012005047  a97808135543107 a10.36019/97808135543102doi  a(DE-B1597)529084  a(OCoLC)814306495  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHT1506b.W56 2012 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aWinkler, Erin N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLearning Race, Learning Place :bShaping Racial Identities and Ideas in African American Childhoods /cErin N. Winkler. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (230 p.) :b7 figures, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Series in Childhood Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Comprehensive Racial Learning, Grounded in Place -- t2. Rhetoric versus Reality: Ambivalence about Race and Racism -- t3. Racialized Place: Comprehensive Racial Learning through Travel -- t4. Place Matters: Shaping Mothers' Messages -- t5. Competing with Society: Responsive Racial Socialization -- t6. Black Is Black? Gender, Skin Tone, and Comprehensive Racial Learning -- t7. Conclusion: "I Learn Being Black from Everywhere I Go" -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn an American society both increasingly diverse and increasingly segregated, the signals children receive about race are more confusing than ever. In this context, how do children negotiate and make meaning of multiple and conflicting messages to develop their own ideas about race? Learning Race, Learning Place engages this question using in-depth interviews with an economically diverse group of African American children and their mothers. Through these rich narratives, Erin N. Winkler seeks to reorient the way we look at how children develop their ideas about race through the introduction of a new framework-comprehensive racial learning-that shows the importance of considering this process from children's points of view and listening to their interpretations of their experiences, which are often quite different from what the adults around them expect or intend. At the children's prompting, Winkler examines the roles of multiple actors and influences, including gender, skin tone, colorblind rhetoric, peers, family, media, school, and, especially, place. She brings to the fore the complex and understudied power of place, positing that while children's racial identities and experiences are shaped by a national construction of race, they are also specific to a particular place that exerts both direct and indirect influence on their racial identities and ideas.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aRacismxStudy and teachingzMichiganzDetroit. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813554310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813554310.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK